        <li><p>([F]) Folland. <em>Real Analysis: Modern Techniques and Their Applications</em>, 2ed.</p></li>
        <li><p>[SS] Stein and Shakarchi. <em>Real Analysis: Measure Theory, Integration, and Hilbert Spaces</em>.</p></li>
        <li><p>[K] Kallenberg. <em>Foundations of Modern Probability</em>, 3ed.</p></li>
    </ul></p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-abstract-measures">
    <title>Abstract measures</title>
    <p>§1.2-1.3.<ul>
      <li><p><m>\sigma</m>-algebra = countably complete Boolean algebra = subset family closed under countable operations (p. 21).</p></li>
      <li><p>Measure = countably additive set function (p. 24).</p></li>
      <li><p>Completion: make subsets of null sets measurable and therefore null (p. 26 Thm. 1.9).</p></li>
      <li><p>Functional factorization: finer <m>\sigma</m>-algebra contains more information and vice versa  ([K] p. 18 Lm. 1.14).</p></li>
      <li><p>Non-measurable sets: having too many measurable sets leads to triviality ([SS] p. 24-25, [F] p. 20).</p></li>
    </ul></p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-outer-measures">
    <title>Outer measures</title>
    <p>§1.4.<ul>
      <li><p>Outer measure can be constructed from any set function by covering (p. 29 Prop. 1.10).</p></li>
      <li><p>Carathéodory's criterion defines measurable sets, on which the outer measure becomes a measure (p. 29 Thm. 1.11).</p></li>
      <li><p>Extension of premeasure: form outer measure and then restrict to measurable sets (p. 31 Prop. 1.13).</p></li>
    </ul></p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-lebesgue-stieltjes-measure">
    <title>Lebesgue-Stieltjes measure</title>
    <p>§1.5.<ul>
      <li><p>Locally finite Borel measures on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> one-to-one correspond to increasing and right continuous functions on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> modding out constants (p. 35 Thm. 1.16). </p></li>
      <li><p>Lebesgue-Stieltjes measures are regular (p. 36 Thm. 1.18). </p></li>
      <li><p>Two exercises: [F] p. 40 Ex. 30-31 = [SS] p. 44 Ex. 28-29 (with hints).</p></li>
    </ul></p>
  </subsection>
